{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9ae3469c-846c-4952-a065-7206425013f1","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process and collect:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps                          # get the PID\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**3. Copy the trace out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**4. Analyze** by opening the `.nettrace` file in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to speedscope:\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\nThen open at [speedscope.app](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**Tips:**\n- 30 seconds is usually enough to capture a hot path.\n- If you can't install tools (read-only filesystem), use a **sidecar** or `dotnet-trace` from a [debug container](https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/debug/debug-application/debug-running-pod/#ephemeral-container): `kubectl debug -it <pod> --image=mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/sdk:8.0 --target=<container>`.\n- For production, consider `--buffersize 256` if you're worried about overhead (default is already low).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ffff068c-4833-4a7d-86eb-00bc8e4ce8d7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a troubleshooting/advisory question, not a code change task. I'll provide concise, practical advice.","outputTokens":457,"requestId":"1B87:FF35F:C7F6E8:E516F9:6A028224"},"id":"40895a3b-24d9-469d-90e6-a1dc93fb4e81","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:28:15.251Z","parentId":"31270856-73c6-44ee-947c-8a5e201b0cba"}
